Salt Lake City (SLC) is a vast desert surrounded by the rocky mountains. At this time ofÂ year, there is still snow on most of the mountains and many higherÂ altitude lakes are still frozen. It looked vaguelyÂ familiar and I could picture John Wayne coming down the mountain.Â What I found amazing was that anyoneÂ wouldÂ settle in a place like SLC, coming over the mountains on wagonsÂ and just seeing miles and miles of featureless plains.Â They were definitely very tough people.

![p1000428](/assets/images/2015/12/p1000428.jpg)

![p1000440](/assets/images/2015/12/p1000440.jpg)

Upon arriving at Brent's house, we got straight into renovatingÂ his bathroom. This was necessary as they wanted to use it during myÂ visit. Academics are theorists and shouldn't be allowed to do anythingÂ too practical. Yogi Berra said, "in theory there is no differenceÂ between theory and practice, in practice there is." All of the bathroom's electrical appliances worked properly except one set of lights.Â Also earlier, a large spark was inadvertently generated due to a short.Â After much bumbling around, we isolated the problem to a loose wire deepÂ in the guts of the wiring. Quietly pleased that nobody got electrocuted,Â I helped Brent fix the rest of the bathroom, hang the door and everythingÂ was operational.

**BYU and the Trip to the Green River**

The next day, I gave a seminar at Brigham Young University (BYU). OneÂ of the best audiences I've spoken to, they asked very good questionsÂ about our work. Anyway, completed my talkÂ without embarrassing myself too much and shortly after, we embarked onÂ the 4 hour drive to the Green River.

On the way, we stopped at a 7-eleven. In the photo below, the smallÂ one on the left is a pint (600 ml) and the big one 1.9 L. I've seen 2 LÂ bottles before but never a 2 L cup. TwoÂ of those are enough to kill you.

